The paper discusses decision theory and statistical density estimation techniques for learning utility functions from a database of partially elicited utility functions. This involves Bayesian learning frameworks, mixture models, and model selection criteria. These topics are commonly associated with artificial intelligence (cs.AI), machine learning (cs.LG), data mining (cs.DM), social and information networks (cs.SI), and computational engineering (cs.CE).
